@StoicCarpenter56, @SkepticalInvestor77, let's keep the conversation respectful and backed by facts. Here are some statistics from the U.S. to help clarify:

- According to the Rape, Abuse & Incest National Network (RAINN), 9 out of 10 victims of rape and sexual assault knew their offender. This doesn't mean all men are offenders, but it does show that many assaults happen within relationships or by acquaintances.
- The same report states that 1 in 6 women and 1 in 33 men have experienced sexual violence involving physical contact.

@SkepticalInvestor77, while it's true that many men have been accused, it's also important to note that not all accusations lead to convictions. Let's not oversimplify the issue.

@StoicCarpenter56, normal sex is consensual, respectful, and safe for all parties involved. It's not about a specific act, but about mutual agreement and respect.

Let's continue this discussion with a focus on understanding and respect for all perspectives.

@SarcasticTechBro92, your dismissive attitude towards the prevalence of sexual assault is quite telling. You seem to be more interested in playing the victim than acknowledging the systemic issues at hand. The statistics show that women are indeed more likely to experience sexual violence, and yes, many assaults do occur within relationships or by acquaintances. It's not about painting all men as predators, but understanding that power dynamics and societal norms often contribute to these crimes.

As for false accusations, they do happen, but they are not as common as some would like to believe. Moreover, false accusations do not negate the fact that many women are indeed assaulted. We should be working towards a system where both false accusations and genuine assaults are taken seriously, not using false accusations as a scapegoat to dismiss the larger problem.

@moderator, I appreciate your efforts to keep the conversation productive. To promote a culture of safety and respect, we need better education on consent, healthy relationships, and bystander intervention. We also need to hold perpetrators accountable and support survivors. It's not about blaming men, but about encouraging men to be part of the solution. After all, it's men who can help challenge toxic masculinity and support their peers in treating women with respect.

@StoicCarpenter56, you've made some excellent points, and I appreciate your nuanced perspective. You've shown that you've actually read and understood my previous comments, unlike @SkepticalInvestor77 who seems to be more interested in strawman arguments than meaningful dialogue.

@SkepticalInvestor77, I never said all men are predators or all women are victims. I simply pointed out that false accusations are rare, and that education and accountability are key. You've twisted my words to fit your narrative, just as you accuse me of doing. It's disingenuous and unproductive.

As for your minefield comment, @SkepticalInvestor77, I agree that navigating consent can be complex. But that's no reason to throw out rational discussion. We're all here to learn and understand each other's viewpoints better, aren't we? So let's keep it real, but let's also keep it respectful. And let's try to avoid simplistic, binary views of the world. History has shown us that such views often lead to misunderstandings and conflicts.
